{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"Included with: <b> πονηρός</b>, ά, όν, <br /> in physical sense, <b>oppressed by toils,</b> πονηρότατος καὶ ἄριστος, of Heracles, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Frr.” 138,139. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of things, <b>toilsome, painful, grievous,</b> ἔργα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus “Epigrammata” 14.20; νούσων πονηρότερον 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 274; φορτίον 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 352. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>in bad case, in sorry plight, useless, good-for-nothing,</b> σύμμαχοι[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 220, compare “Nu.” 102; στράτευμα 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 3.4.34; ἰατρός 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 4.2.4 (variant for{μοχθηρός})\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; κύων, ἱππάριον, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 298d, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.4.19 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δίαιτα, τροφή, σιτία, <b>injurious,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 425e, “Lg.” 735b, “Grg.” 464d, etc.; π. ἕξις σώματος [prev. author] “Ti.” 86e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. σῶμα, opposed to χρηστόν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Prt.” 313a, compare “R.” 341e \">Refs</a>]; π. σκώμματα <b>sorry</b> jests, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 542; π. βούλευμα [prev. author] “Lys.” 517 (_comparative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. πράγματα a <b>bad</b> state of things, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.97, compare 24 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. ἀρχὴ τῆς παιδείας a <b>bad</b> beginning, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.11; π. τὴν ναυτιλίαν ναυτίλλεσθαι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 551c; π. πολιτεία 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1294b38. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <i>adverb</i>, -ρῶς ἔχειν to be <b>in bad case,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.83, etc.; ἂ πονηρῶς ἔχει τῶν πραγμάτων 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 14.35 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. διακεῖσθαι, διατεθῆναι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 19.12, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 59.55. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> in moral sense, <b>worthless, knavish,</b> φήμη, βίος, ζόη, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 1045, “Frr.” 90,401, etc.; οὐδεὶς ἑκὼν π. 5th c.BC: Epicharmus Comicus 78; π. ἦθος 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 192 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πονηρὸς.. κἀκ πονηρῶν <b>rogue</b> and son <b>of rogues,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 336 - 7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὦ πόνῳ πονηρέ in a comic jingle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “V.” 466, compare “Lys.” 350 \">Refs</a>]; π. πόρρω τέχνης past master in <b>knavery,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “V.” 192; π. τοῖς φίλοις 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.4.33; πρὸς ἀλλήλους [prev. author] “An.” 7.1.39; π. λόγων ἀκρίβεια 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 3.3.3; πονηρότεροι σύμβουλοι [prev. author] 5.71 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. [ῥῆμα] <b>malicious,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"NT.Matt.5.11; τὰ π. \">NT</a>]<b>wickednesses,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 2.2.25; πονηρὰ δρᾶσαι 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 1190; τὸ π. LXX.Deu.17.2 \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]; δόλῳ πονηρῷ, Latin <i>dolo malo</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 693.6 (Methymna, 2nd c.BC)\">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]; ὁ π. the <b>evil one,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"NT.Matt.13.19; π. δαίμων “PLips.” 34.8 (4th c.AD), etc. \">NT+4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> <b>base, cowardly,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 437, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. χρώματα, i.e. the coward's hue, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 5.2.34 (interpolated). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> with a political connotation, <b>of the baser sort,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 424; οἱ λεγόμενοι π. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 519a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to καλοὶ κἀγαθοί, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 15.100,316, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 186.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —On the variation of accent, πονηρός and πόνηρος, see at {μοχθηρός} near the end","strongNumber":"G4191","accentedUnicode":"πονηρότερος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G4189","matchingForm":"πονηρία","stepTransliteration":"ponēria","gloss":"evil","_zh_tw_Gloss":"邪惡","_es_Gloss":"maldad","_zh_Gloss":"邪恶"},{"strongNumber":"G4190","matchingForm":"πονηρός","stepTransliteration":"ponēros","gloss":"evil/bad","_zh_tw_Gloss":"惡","_es_Gloss":"malvado/malo","_zh_Gloss":"恶"}],"shortDef":"- more evil","mediumDef":"- more evil evil, wicked, painful, harmful","stepGloss":"more evil","stepTransliteration":"ponēroteros","count":0,"_es_Definition":"peor","_zh_tw_Definition":"更惡的,此…更惡的,邪惡的","_zh_Definition":"更恶的,此…更恶的,邪恶的","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"ác hơn; xấu hơn. Xem G4190","_zh_tw_Gloss":"邪惡","_es_Gloss":"más malvado","_zh_Gloss":"邪恶"}]}